  "image": "C:\\CorbinOrdelStudio\\2026\\TheLittleLabs\\extension-1tribe-interactive-official\\public\\rive\\TheWildLifeHummingbirdforaDay_83230\\word-hotspots\\hummingbird_spread_08.png",
  "text": "Time for breakfast! Or is this your second breakfast-or third? Three meals a day aren't nearly enough. You must eat all day long to have the energy to keep flying. Flowers are your main food source. so you visit hundreds of them every day' You like red. orange. and pink flowers best. though flowers of any color will do. As you hover over a flower to drink its nectar. your wings beat so fast that they make a humming sound. You drink more than your body weight in nectar every day For a kid. that would be like eating about grilled cheese sandwiches in a day' Your tongue is forked. When you dip it inside a flower. it splits in two. which helps you get even more nectar You can extend your tongue. too! Tiny. rough. hairlike fringes on your tongue called lamellae help trap the nectar as you sip it. letting you gulp down as mach as possible' Nectar is sweet and has a healthy kind of sugar that gives you energy to fly. You know how much sugar is in the nectar you drink from each flower. tf a flower's too low in sugar. you won't feed on it. WHAT IS POLLINATION? You are important to the polEnation process. which helps plants make seeds and multiply. When you dip into a flower. it covers your head and bill with yellow pollen. Then. when you visit another flower. you transfer that pollen to it. the pollen fertilizes cells in the flowers to make seeds. which create more flowers. You pollinate thousands of different wildflowers and plants. keeping them alive and beautiful. and giving living things more food to eat! MmmrvNrd EAT LIKE A HUMMINGBIRD Hover above a flower that has a lot of nectar. Place your bill inside the flower. Open your bill and extend your long. forked tongue. Extend your lamellae to lap up the nectar. Put your tongue back in your mouth and absorb the liquid. Repeat hundreds of times each day!",
